{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T17:52:16.801Z",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gradients point downhill on the loss surface—but how far to step, and how to combine past gradients, determines whether training converges in hours or diverges entirely. Optimizers turn gradients into weight updates; learning rate schedules control step size over time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gradient descent",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " updates each parameter by moving opposite to its gradient: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "w = w - lr * grad",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "lr",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "learning rate",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stochastic gradient descent (SGD)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " uses mini-batch gradients (noisy but fast). "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimizers",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " like Adam and AdamW adapt per-parameter step sizes using momentum and variance estimates."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM pretraining runs for weeks on thousands of GPUs with carefully tuned learning rates, warmup, and decay. Fine-tuning often uses smaller learning rates (1e-5 to 1e-4) with AdamW. Wrong optimizer settings cause loss spikes, catastrophic forgetting, or wasted compute. Production training configs list optimizer type, betas, weight decay, and schedule—this topic decodes those choices."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Basic gradient descent"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Manual SGD step\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    for param in model.parameters():\n        param -= learning_rate * param.grad"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SGD with momentum"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Maintains a velocity vector: updates accumulate direction over steps, smoothing noisy batch gradients and accelerating convergence in consistent directions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01, momentum=0.9)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adam and AdamW"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adam tracks exponential moving averages of gradients (momentum) and squared gradients (adaptive scaling). Each parameter gets its own effective learning rate. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "AdamW",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " decouples weight decay from the adaptive update—standard for transformer training and fine-tuning."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(\n    model.parameters(),\n    lr=2e-5,\n    betas=(0.9, 0.999),\n    weight_decay=0.01,\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Learning rate schedules"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Warmup",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — linearly increase lr from 0 over first N steps; stabilizes early training of large models"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cosine decay",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — smoothly reduce lr to a floor; common in LLM pretraining"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Linear decay",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — drop lr proportionally to remaining steps; common in fine-tuning"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from torch.optim.lr_scheduler import CosineAnnealingLR\n\nscheduler = CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=1000)\nfor step in range(1000):\n    train_step()\n    optimizer.step()\n    scheduler.step()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Batch size and effective learning rate"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Larger batches produce lower-variance gradient estimates. Linear scaling rule: when batch size doubles, lr can often double (up to a point). LLM training uses large batches distributed across many devices with gradient accumulation to simulate even larger effective batches."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Examples"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "model = nn.Linear(768, 768)\noptimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-4)\ncriterion = nn.MSELoss()\n\nfor batch in dataloader:\n    optimizer.zero_grad()\n    out = model(batch.x)\n    loss = criterion(out, batch.y)\n    loss.backward()\n    torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=1.0)\n    optimizer.step()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trade-offs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "SGD",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — simple, generalizes well with tuning; slower per step than Adam on some problems"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Adam/AdamW",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — fast convergence, forgiving default hyperparameters; can generalize slightly worse than tuned SGD in some vision tasks, but dominant for transformers"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Large learning rate",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — faster progress but risk of divergence; warmup mitigates"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Small learning rate",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — stable but slow; may underfit if too conservative during fine-tuning"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Weight decay",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — regularizes weights; too high shrinks capacity, too low allows overfitting"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Learning rate too high",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — loss NaNs or spikes; reduce lr or increase warmup."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Forgetting scheduler.step()",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — lr stays constant when schedule intended; training behaves unexpectedly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Tuning lr on full model first",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — lr range tests on a small subset save hours before full fine-tunes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Different lrs for new vs pretrained layers",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — sometimes intentional (discriminative fine-tuning), but accidental mismatch freezes progress in one part of the network."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Not using weight decay with AdamW",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — conflating L2 penalty in Adam vs decoupled decay in AdamW leads to wrong regularization."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Best practices"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Default fine-tuning starting point: AdamW, lr 1e-5 to 2e-5, linear warmup 5–10% of steps, weight decay 0.01."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Log learning rate alongside loss every step."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use gradient clipping (max norm 1.0) for transformer training stability."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Run short lr sweeps (e.g., 1e-6, 3e-6, 1e-5, 3e-5) on a validation slice before long runs."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Match optimizer settings to the base model's fine-tuning recipe when reproducing results."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mental model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Imagine loss as a hilly landscape and weights as your position. The gradient is the steepest downhill direction. Gradient descent takes small steps downhill. Momentum is rolling downhill—you pick up speed in consistent directions. Adam is a smart hiker who takes bigger steps on flat terrain and smaller steps on steep, uneven ground. Learning rate schedule is deciding to take smaller steps as you near a valley floor."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Optimizers convert gradients into parameter updates; learning rate controls step size."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "AdamW with warmup + decay is the default recipe for transformer and LLM training."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Batch size, gradient accumulation, and lr scaling interact—effective batch size matters."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Clip gradients and monitor loss spikes to catch instability early."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Fine-tuning uses much smaller learning rates than training a small MLP from scratch."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
